{"meta":{"authors":[{"id":"7","fullname":"José I. Cabezón"}],"title":"Exorcism","dates":{"created_at":"2013-09-15 04:08:39 UTC","updated_at":"2014-02-27 19:17:44 UTC"}},"nodes":[{"index":0,"parent_index":-1,"title":"Exorcism"},{"title":"Description","index":1,"parent_index":0,"body":"\n<p>This category overlaps with \"<a href=\"../../../../../features/2380\">Protection rituals</a>\" (<em>bsrung</em>) and \"<a href=\"../../../../../features/1908\">Destruction rituals</a>\" (<em>grol, bsad</em>), as the three form a common triad <em>bsrung bzlog bsad gsum</em>.</p>\n<p>Protection rituals usually anticipate the attack of opposing forces, providing a first line of defense before an attack takes place. Exorcisms, on the other hand, usually serve to turn back attacks that have already taken place. In extreme cases, enemies (humans or spirits) may be killed using destructive rituals.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>The \"Exorcism\" Knowledge Map category is also used for \"ransom\" rituals, which often use effegies to repurchase one's soul or life-force.</p>\n"},{"title":"Related Terms","index":2,"parent_index":0,"body":"\n<p>bzlog bsgyur, bskrad thabs, 'grol ba, glud, dbang sdud, zhi bar byed pa, 'dul ba, gto, gto yas, gto 'bol</p>\n"},{"title":"Example Texts","index":3,"parent_index":0,"body":"\n<ul>\n<li>See also <a href=\"http://tbrc.org/#!rid=T1726\">bzlog bsgyur</a></li>\n</ul>\n"},{"title":"Secondary Sources","index":4,"parent_index":0,"body":"\n<p><!--[if gte mso 9]><xml> Normal   0         false   false   false                             MicrosoftInternetExplorer4 </xml><![endif]--><!--[if gte mso 9]><xml> </xml><![endif]--><!--[if !mso]> <span class=\"mceItemObject\"   classid=\"clsid:38481807-CA0E-42D2-BF39-B33AF135CC4D\" id=ieooui> </span> <mce:style><!  st1\\:*{behavior:url(#i<![endif]--> <!--[endif]--><!--  --><!--[if gte mso 10]> <mce:style><!   /* Style Definitions */  table.MsoNormalTable \t{mso-style-name:\"Table Normal\"; \tmso-tstyle-rowband-size:0; \tmso-tstyle-colband